<div id="review_3674066590" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3674066590" />
    <a title="Allie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117420861-allie"><img alt="Allie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607277013p2/117420861.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3674066590?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Allie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Allie" href="/user/show/117420861-allie">Allie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3674066590" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer747835608843081952">I fell in love with the vivid imagery as she recounted her youth, from the way her mom seemed to perpetually smell of fresh oregano to the taste of sancocho or creamy rice with milk....to the pigs and the little eggs they collected from their chickens. I was enraptured by this book. I could almost feel the Puerto Rican soil, the jíbara soul. I could hear the novenas being prayed for the dead. I could taste the pasteles and hear the bickering of her parents. I could feel her fear moving to New Yo</span>
  <span id="freeText747835608843081952" style="display:none">I fell in love with the vivid imagery as she recounted her youth, from the way her mom seemed to perpetually smell of fresh oregano to the taste of sancocho or creamy rice with milk....to the pigs and the little eggs they collected from their chickens. I was enraptured by this book. I could almost feel the Puerto Rican soil, the jíbara soul. I could hear the novenas being prayed for the dead. I could taste the pasteles and hear the bickering of her parents. I could feel her fear moving to New York, and the pride in which she felt at getting to where she is today. I loved this book so much. </span>
  <a data-text-id="747835608843081952" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


